Conjecture: Let $x_{1}, x_{2}, \cdots, x_{n} \in \overline{\mathbf{R}^{-}}$, and $x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2} \leqslant n-1$, prove or disprove:
(1) $\frac{1}{2}(n-1)(n-2)+(n-1) x_{1} x_{2} \cdots x_{n} \geqslant \sum_{1<i<j<n} x_{i} x_{j}$;
(2) $n-1+x_{1} x_{2} \cdots x_{n} \geqslant x_{1}+x_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}$;
(3) $1+(n-1) x_{1} x_{2} \cdots x_{n} \geqslant \sum x_{2} x_{3} \cdots x_{n}$.

Equality holds in all three inequalities if and only if one of $x_{1}, x_{2}, \cdots, x_{n}$ is 0 and the other $n-1$ are all equal to 1. Here $\sum x_{2} x_{3} \cdots x_{n}$ denotes the sum of the products of every $n-1$ numbers among $x_{1}, x_{2}, \cdots, x_{n}$.

